04746nam a22007935i 9783110753042DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107530427 a10.1515/97831107530422doi  a(DE-B1597)584732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBM659.S3 7aREL0062102bisacsh04a296.4/152231 aMoore, James D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiterary Depictions of the Scribal Profession in the Story of Ahiqar and Jeremiah 36 /cJames D. Moore. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 212 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die alttestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0934-2575 ;v54100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContent -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Allusions to the Aramaic Scribal Profession in the Story of Ahiqar -- t3. Allusions to the Hebrew Scribal Profession in the Tale of Jeremiah and Baruch’s Scroll -- t4. The Story of Ahiqar and the Tale of Jeremiah and Baruch’s Scroll in Comparative Perspective -- t5. Conclusion -- tAppendix: Syriac Ahiqar Manuscripts Cited -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Ancient Sources -- tSelected Terms Discussed -- tAbbreviations0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first study to compare the allusions to scribal culture found in the Aramaic Story of Ahiqar and the Hebrew Tale of Jeremiah and Baruch’s Scroll in Jeremiah 36. It is shown that disguised in the royal propagandistic message of Ahiqar is a sophisticated Aramaic critique on the social practices of Akkadian scribal culture. Jeremiah 36, however, uses loci of scribal activity as well as allusions to scribal interactions and the techniques of the scribal craft to construct a subversive tale. When studied from a comparative perspective it is argued that the Story of Ahiqar, which has long been associated with the well-known court tale genre, is an example of a subgenre which is here called the scribal conflict narrative, and Jeremiah 36 is found to be a second example of or a response to it. This observation is arrived at by means of rigorous manuscript examination combined with narrative analysis, which identified, among other things, the development of autobiographical and biographical styles of the same ancient narrative. This study not only provides new perspectives on scribal culture, Ahiqar studies, and Jeremiah studies, but it may have far reaching implications for other ancient sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJewsxHistoryy586 B.C.-70 A.D. 0aScribes, Jewish. 4aAchiqar. 4aAltes Testament. 4aJeremia. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aAhiqar.  aBaruch's Scroll.  aJeremia.  aScribal Culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107531270 cprintz978311075254040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311075304240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110753042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110753042/original  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075419-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGFb2021